I'll tell you what.

1254
01:49:37,301 --> 01:49:37,921
I'll tell you, Roger.

1255
01:49:37,941 --> 01:49:39,522
When I experience it, I'll let you know.

1256
01:49:39,942 --> 01:49:40,182
All right.

1257
01:49:40,282 --> 01:49:40,502
All right.

1258
01:49:40,522 --> 01:49:41,162
We'll let you go.

1259
01:49:41,182 --> 01:49:42,642
Thanks very much indeed, Rahul.

1260
01:49:42,742 --> 01:49:52,565
Now, the reason I was asking Rahul that rather strange and fairly philosophical question is that we are interested in a case that's come up in Nigeria.

1261
01:49:52,625 --> 01:50:02,127
Now, the governor of Nigeria's Imo state, Rojas Okorocha, has appointed his sister as commissioner for happiness and couples fulfillment.

1262
01:50:02,787 --> 01:50:08,348
The governor's spokesman said there wasn't anything unusual about the appointment, as Mr Okorocha always wanted to make people happy.

1263
01:50:09,148 --> 01:50:16,030
Well, I've been speaking to Yemi Adamokolekun, who is one of the founders of the campaign called Enough is Enough Nigeria.

1264
01:50:16,610 --> 01:50:20,211
It's a good governance advocacy group based in Lagos.

1265
01:50:21,091 --> 01:50:26,092
Now, she says a minister of happiness isn't perhaps as absurd as it sounds.

1266
01:50:26,715 --> 01:50:37,907
The UAE actually has one, and the role of the Minister of Happiness is a person who oversees the UAE's plans, programmes and policies to achieve a happier society.

1267
01:50:38,047 --> 01:50:40,310
So there's a clear mandate for a Minister of Happiness.

1268
01:50:40,850 --> 01:50:43,313
But we need to define what happiness is, I suppose.

1269
01:50:43,373 --> 01:50:47,478
I mean, you and I might agree, we might disagree on what happiness exactly is.

1270
01:50:47,838 --> 01:50:48,418
Well, yes.

1271
01:50:48,598 --> 01:50:56,281
According to the lady who was tweeting earlier today, she's been responsible for hospitality for the Imo State government for the last six years.

1272
01:50:56,822 --> 01:51:04,585
So it was considered it was a natural fit for her to continue to make provisions for large Christmas tree, catering for statewide events.

1273
01:51:04,925 --> 01:51:10,747
So things that relate to fun occasions that the state organizes she was responsible for.

1274
01:51:10,887 --> 01:51:14,849
So in their definition, it's just fun events.

1275
01:51:15,429 --> 01:51:17,090
Fun events equals happy society.

1276
01:51:18,110 --> 01:51:29,260
I mean, fun and happiness, I suppose, again, philosophically, you might not think of the same thing, but I mean, maybe if people had more money or didn't have to worry about illness, I mean, those kind of things might bring them happiness.

1277
01:51:29,700 --> 01:51:31,522
Most definitely, especially in this context.

1278
01:51:31,582 --> 01:51:37,267
So the governor of Imo, for example, is owing pensioners, I think, either 14 or 16 months of salaries.

1279
01:51:37,987 --> 01:51:47,837
So I would agree with you that if those ones actually were able to meet their basic needs they will be quite quite happy rather than having a Christmas tree to go and look at.

1280
01:51:48,237 --> 01:51:56,745
I'm detecting you don't think this is a particularly well that this is in the end a fairly absurd thing to do to a Minister for Happiness when that kind of thing's going on.

1281
01:51:57,045 --> 01:52:02,030
Yeah in this context I mean the UAE it's quite okay for them to have a Minister of Happiness because if you have

1282
01:52:02,710 --> 01:52:08,614
The GDP per capita that they do and sort of income inequality is not a major issue in the UAE.

1283
01:52:09,214 --> 01:52:18,679
In Nigeria it is a huge issue and especially in the state in question where there are evidence that the governor is not spending the state's resources judiciously.

1284
01:52:19,120 --> 01:52:21,621
So large Christmas tree, lavish events.

1285
01:52:21,661 --> 01:52:26,284
I think for his birthday there were like 25 cakes stacked on top of each other.

1286
01:52:26,884 --> 01:52:32,869
And then in recent months, he's done a statue of Jacob Zuba, and Jacob Zuba flew in to commission the statue.

1287
01:52:33,330 --> 01:52:37,473
Spending state resources on things like that, to me, are just quite absurd.

1288
01:52:37,834 --> 01:52:40,456
And you don't really need a Minister of Happiness to make people happy.

1289
01:52:40,496 --> 01:52:44,820
You just need to respond to their needs to be able to meet their basic needs.

1290
01:52:45,320 --> 01:52:47,182
But it's made this lady quite happy, I suppose.

1291
01:52:47,522 --> 01:52:48,023
I'm indeed.

1292
01:52:48,163 --> 01:52:51,148
She's actually the minister, the governor's biological sister.

1293
01:52:51,169 --> 01:52:58,701
So she's quite comfortable in the role that she's been given and she, according to her tweet, is looking forward to doing more to make the people of Imo happy.

1294
01:52:59,835 --> 01:53:08,841
Yemi, that set us all to thinking about whether governments or that kind of thing could actually talk about happiness in this sort of way.

1295
01:53:08,881 --> 01:53:10,022
Is it quantifiable?

1296
01:53:10,062 --> 01:53:16,947
I mean, Andrew, I do remember it was Bhutan, I think, started talking about the gross national happiness and somehow they could go towards that.

1297
01:53:16,967 --> 01:53:18,588
I mean, do you believe that's possible?

1298
01:53:19,808 --> 01:53:22,010
I'm pretty skeptical, I'm afraid, Roger.

1299
01:53:22,170 --> 01:53:38,383
My concern here is, I remember a few years ago, David Cameron, former UK Prime Minister, when he was in opposition, during the years running up to the financial crisis, he would say, well, you know, we've got to start thinking beyond GDP growth, and we've got to start thinking about the happiness of people.

1300
01:53:38,783 --> 01:53:40,985
And then, of course, the financial crisis hit, and everyone was

1301
01:53:41,485 --> 01:53:44,526
thinking, crikey, we've got to sort out the economy here first.

1302
01:53:44,546 --> 01:53:59,013
And it seems to me that when people start talking about this sort of thing, it's a it's a sort of worrying counter cyclical sign that we're getting a bit complacent about things and that actually government should stick to the knitting of just running the country competently.

1303
01:53:59,633 --> 01:54:03,637
And whether I'm happy or not, I'll decide for myself.

1304
01:54:03,697 --> 01:54:07,441
But as long as the country is run well, that's what I want from my government.

1305
01:54:07,461 --> 01:54:09,142
Well, that's an interesting one, actually.

1306
01:54:09,222 --> 01:54:11,825
Tony, isn't the problem his definition?

1307
01:54:11,865 --> 01:54:12,846
I mean, what is happening?

1308
01:54:12,866 --> 01:54:15,909
Some people are happy with one thing, other people are not.

1309
01:54:16,569 --> 01:54:18,371
You can't really quantify or measure it, can you?

1310
01:54:19,737 --> 01:54:24,621
No, you can't, although I'm sure I'm not the only one who's thinking about it here at the end of the year.

1311
01:54:25,662 --> 01:54:27,824
This is a fascinating story.

1312
01:54:27,844 --> 01:54:28,284
I'm not sure.

1313
01:54:28,304 --> 01:54:31,367
I think I come down on Andy's side with this.

1314
01:54:31,407 --> 01:54:38,733
I think stability, consistency in government would make me very happy.

1315
01:54:38,793 --> 01:54:39,233
Well, there we are.

1316
01:54:39,253 --> 01:54:40,854
You see, now you have defined it a bit.

1317
01:54:40,894 --> 01:54:43,135
I mean, surely, Tony, there must be other things that make you happy.

1318
01:54:43,155 --> 01:54:43,495
For me?

1319
01:54:43,695 --> 01:54:47,217
Yeah, which perhaps, you know, you could make a list and say, right, that's fine.

1320
01:54:47,697 --> 01:54:48,618
Now I can get that.

1321
01:54:48,638 --> 01:54:50,138
I can even ask the government for it.

1322
01:54:50,178 --> 01:54:51,679
And then I shall achieve happiness.

1323
01:54:51,719 --> 01:54:52,780
Isn't that the way forward?

1324
01:54:54,460 --> 01:54:54,901
Yeah, I suppose.

1325
01:54:54,941 --> 01:54:58,162
I don't know if you need a commissioner for that.

1326
01:54:58,262 --> 01:54:59,123
All right, then, come on.

1327
01:54:59,143 --> 01:55:00,383
What would make you happy, Tony?

1328
01:55:01,804 --> 01:55:03,325
Just a few achievable things.

1329
01:55:03,385 --> 01:55:03,925
Come on.

1330
01:55:04,005 --> 01:55:05,466
It's getting towards the end of the year.

1331
01:55:05,846 --> 01:55:07,447
People might be thinking what to give you for Christmas.

1332
01:55:07,467 --> 01:55:07,827
You never know.

1333
01:55:08,863 --> 01:55:10,483
A giant Christmas tree sounds great.

1334
01:55:10,623 --> 01:55:15,565
I think if our government could get right on that for me or for whoever, you know, I'd appreciate it.

1335
01:55:16,425 --> 01:55:26,927
Andrew, it's an interesting, the part of the world you are, there is in some ways a more, I don't know, a mechanical attitude perhaps to some of the things that can bring happiness.

1336
01:55:26,947 --> 01:55:29,548
People think, well, we will get this and that and the government can bring it.

1337
01:55:30,328 --> 01:55:35,391
and they can make it happen and then we will have a nice utilitarian kind of paradise.

1338
01:55:35,792 --> 01:55:41,055
I mean, do you think that's particularly something that in your part of the world, in Asia, is more of a thing people think about?

1339
01:55:42,535 --> 01:55:48,819
I think people in this part of the world, particularly in Hong Kong, happiness is quite associated with wealth.

1340
01:55:49,780 --> 01:55:50,661
Let's put it that way.

1341
01:55:51,902 --> 01:56:02,689
And I think certainly in Hong Kong, as long as the government kind of gets out of the way and lets people get on and make money, then that's what makes the people here generally happy.

1342
01:56:03,129 --> 01:56:19,055
I mean obviously on the mainland in China you have a slightly different approach where the government sort of is responsible for most things including the delivery of happiness to the people and I just worry that that is not exactly the way that countries are best run.

1343
01:56:19,315 --> 01:56:21,276
Is that because it's a very materialistic way?

1344
01:56:21,316 --> 01:56:32,240
I mean we think of a lot of course of philosophy coming out of Asia as well but is there a certain materialism you know that happiness is measurable as you say in wealth terms it's clear.

1345
01:56:34,528 --> 01:56:40,911
You could argue that these are quite heavy topics for a Thursday morning.

1346
01:56:41,271 --> 01:56:49,194
I think, look, I don't want to generalize too much about Hong Kongers in the sense that I don't want to tar them with just being interested in money.

1347
01:56:49,254 --> 01:56:55,276
But I do think that it is a feature of the society out here.

1348
01:56:56,757 --> 01:56:59,798
And perhaps that comes from historical background where

1349
01:57:00,258 --> 01:57:19,127
you know, people have had to work hard for a living here and in this part of the world and so the attainment of a certain level of standard of living is something that's associated with happiness and you can't blame people for that if, you know, they've come from a generally poor background and a poor historical background.

1350
01:57:19,428 --> 01:57:22,489
All right, well finally then, Andrew, what would constitute happiness for you?

1351
01:57:22,529 --> 01:57:23,770
Come on, I've put Tony through this.

1352
01:57:24,570 --> 01:57:25,891
I was pretty happy over the weekend.

1353
01:57:25,911 --> 01:57:29,133
I was sat watching England play Australia in Adelaide.

1354
01:57:29,573 --> 01:57:32,495
What would have made me happier is if England had been playing a bit better.

1355
01:57:32,515 --> 01:57:33,956
I was going to say the outcome, but we didn't.

1356
01:57:34,677 --> 01:57:35,417
I'm a simple guy.

1357
01:57:36,338 --> 01:57:39,740
Good game of cricket, but England winning is what makes me happy.

1358
01:57:39,760 --> 01:57:40,420
All right.

1359
01:57:40,600 --> 01:57:40,660
OK.

1360
01:57:40,680 --> 01:57:42,241
Well, we'll send you on your way happy.

1361
01:57:42,442 --> 01:57:44,743
And Tony, we hope we send you on your way too.

1362
01:57:44,763 --> 01:57:46,284
Perhaps you will get that large Christmas tree.

1363
01:57:46,784 --> 01:57:49,486
And as for me, well, it's the end of the programme and I get to go to bed.

1364
01:57:49,686 --> 01:57:50,727
What could be a better happiness?

1365
01:57:50,747 --> 01:57:51,707
Thank you very much for listening.

1366
01:57:52,028 --> 01:57:52,648
That's it from us.

1367
01:57:52,968 --> 01:57:53,769
Back same time tomorrow.

