because it did strike me from the very beginning knowing a little about your life story that when you address this issue of fathers and sons the balance between sort of being the guide and the authority figure but also the caring and loving figure and it was obvious that the son liked him in the end

2042
03:09:08,768 --> 03:09:18,440
Indeed, but you didn't have that because your father, as I understand it, he quit the family home in Istanbul for a long period to go and try and find his writer's voice.

2043
03:09:18,500 --> 03:09:19,241
He would disappear for a while.

2044
03:09:19,281 --> 03:09:19,701
He went to Paris.

2045
03:09:19,721 --> 03:09:27,090
Yes, he went to Paris following footsteps of Jean-Paul Sartre in Paris, hotels, he wrote diaries which he gave me.

2046
03:09:27,331 --> 03:09:28,232
Did you feel betrayed?

2047
03:09:28,612 --> 03:09:31,834
No, and when you're a child, you don't feel betrayed.

2048
03:09:32,134 --> 03:09:43,842
Also, since my father was not a Freudian father, a father that perhaps Baudelaire would have hated, oppressing his son, he always said, I'm your best friend.

2049
03:09:44,422 --> 03:09:50,128
And, in fact, my Freudian father may be my brother who taught me things, who was stronger.

2050
03:09:50,408 --> 03:09:58,917
My father always had fun with us, and he treated us as if we are me and my brother geniuses, and never suppressed us.

2051
03:09:59,458 --> 03:10:04,643
While, on the other hand, this other father was more attentive to the boy than my father.

2052
03:10:04,843 --> 03:10:21,644
See, your book raises this fascinating question about the way in which individuals develop, the balance between being taught and disciplined and finding your own path, your own identity and individual personality.

2053
03:10:22,384 --> 03:10:24,086
You seem to suggest that if

2054
03:10:24,927 --> 03:10:31,130
The character in the book, Jem, had had an active father throughout his life.

2055
03:10:31,651 --> 03:10:35,853
He might have been different and he might actually have struggled to find his own voice more.

2056
03:10:35,953 --> 03:10:38,194
And I wonder if you feel that about your very self.

2057
03:10:39,175 --> 03:10:52,602
I was influenced by my father first because he had a good library when he was continuously reading books but never telling me that you have to read this, you have to read that, just being an example without doing anything.

2058
03:10:53,242 --> 03:11:10,505
And also, my father's, this is more important, my father's heroes were not, as in most of the time, as in Turkey, soldiers, police, religious notables, political notables, statemen, but my father's heroes were Jean Paul Sartre and Albert Camus or others.

2059
03:11:11,025 --> 03:11:20,127
other fashionable but deep philosophical authors of the time and I thought I have to be like that but he never said to me you have to be like that.

2060
03:11:20,147 --> 03:11:34,210
It seems to me all Orhan Pamuk novels work on many different levels and many of them are somewhat allegorical and it seems to me this relationship between the well digger and his apprentice who sees him as a father figure for the absent father that he never really had

2061
03:11:34,970 --> 03:11:46,977
It is also an allegory, it seems, for Turkey and a desire in Turkey to look up to a figure of authority and the balance between individualism and authoritarianism in your country.

2062
03:11:47,057 --> 03:11:53,120
And today you have President Erdogan, who perhaps would like to see himself as the father of the nation.

2063
03:11:53,440 --> 03:11:56,562
Was that in your mind as you wrote this book about fathers?

2064
03:11:56,682 --> 03:12:04,325
At the beginning, it was not in my mind that this story of fathers and sons stayed with me many, many years.

2065
03:12:04,706 --> 03:12:09,848
Then I thought about it, and I have, I must confess, projects like that all around me.

2066
03:12:10,288 --> 03:12:17,012
I did the interview, someone typed it up, and I carried it with me as I do, even in my travels, thinking what to do with it.

2067
03:12:17,732 --> 03:12:37,045
Then, after a while, I decided to write a book comparing Sophocles' Oedipus Rex, which is about killing the father without knowing it, and Firdevsi, the famous, the most distinguished Persian classic, which also influenced the whole Ottoman Empire.

2068
03:12:37,446 --> 03:12:40,448
Firdevsi is called Book of Kings, Shahnameh.

2069
03:12:41,548 --> 03:12:54,074
which is a sea of stories, in which there is one particular story, Ruslam and Sohrab, which almost mirror images, mirror reflects Oedipus and his father.

2070
03:12:54,094 --> 03:13:01,798
You have a Western classic sort of myth, which is the son killing the father by accident, and then you have an Eastern Persian

2071
03:13:02,458 --> 03:13:08,823
similarly, a sort of mythical story in which in the end a father kills a son.

2072
03:13:08,843 --> 03:13:26,395
Would it be right to say that what you portray is, and again a lot of allegory is involved, but you use these two myths, one that comes classically from the West, one that comes from Persia and the East, you show the way that both play out in this story of the characters in your book.

2073
03:13:27,315 --> 03:13:38,503
And in essence, what you seem to be saying is that Turkey remains pulled in these different directions, Western tradition, Eastern tradition, somehow finding a path between the two.

2074
03:13:38,864 --> 03:13:52,574
But is it your feeling that right now, the Eastern tradition, to use the allegories, the father kills the son, the authority figure is the survivor, is that your feeling about Turkey today?

2075
03:13:53,694 --> 03:13:59,396
Now, to answer your previous question, where you said, is this an accident, coincidence, that you wrote this?

2076
03:13:59,496 --> 03:13:59,696
No.

2077
03:14:00,157 --> 03:14:01,297
The story stayed with me.

2078
03:14:01,577 --> 03:14:13,422
But I thought, my God, then associating the father who kills his son, then I can also write this book in such a way that alludes to what's happening in Turkey.

2079
03:14:13,762 --> 03:14:17,403
Yes, Turkey is increasingly getting authoritarian.

2080
03:14:17,883 --> 03:14:19,184
Though I had this story

2081
03:14:19,924 --> 03:14:26,511
the well-digger and his disciple, a desire to compare Sophocles and Ferdowsi.

2082
03:14:26,851 --> 03:14:42,347
But yes, in the last two years, when I was busy with this book, I was thinking also, I am alluding and writing almost a fictional inquiry into the roots of Middle Eastern, Asian, Muslim authoritarianism.

2083
03:14:42,787 --> 03:15:01,221
Orhan Pamuk, let's be honest, do you have to write in this form of allegory and almost code, because if you wrote directly about what you see happening in Turkey today, you would run the risk of, frankly, censorship, repression, and as we've seen with some writers, even imprisonment.

2084
03:15:01,361 --> 03:15:02,102
Good question.

2085
03:15:02,322 --> 03:15:09,728
I never had, even in this horrible state that we are politically in, and maybe I'll explain why horrible, I'm calling it horrible,

2086
03:15:10,709 --> 03:15:29,622
You know, everyone knows that some 15 months ago there was a horrible attempt to do a military coup, then after that came a purge, and during the purge 130,000 people were fired from their jobs, and these people cannot go back to their work, and some of them even cannot work in private business.

2087
03:15:30,082 --> 03:15:34,564
have hundreds of journalists, writers, academics locked up.

2088
03:15:35,024 --> 03:15:46,648
And 50,000 people are jailed and the government needs more prisons and they're announcing their thing and around 180 or 70 journalists are in jail.

2089
03:15:46,668 --> 03:15:50,889
This is the situation of the country and I'm writing my novel in this situation.

2090
03:15:51,129 --> 03:15:52,730
But even in this situation

2091
03:15:53,190 --> 03:15:56,573
I don't think I will ever have a problem with any novel that I want.

2092
03:15:56,833 --> 03:16:00,136
This never happened to me in Turkey, nor to anyone.

2093
03:16:00,677 --> 03:16:02,338
But you will have... Why is that?

2094
03:16:02,418 --> 03:16:03,960
Is it because you self-censor?

2095
03:16:04,040 --> 03:16:05,541
Is it because you are so careful?

2096
03:16:11,306 --> 03:16:23,011
selecting your subject matter, your characters and your words with a knowledge of how to sort of send messages without upsetting the system.

2097
03:16:23,031 --> 03:16:23,571
No, it's not.

2098
03:16:23,931 --> 03:16:30,714
If I want to send messages like that, as we are going to do now, I am always outspoken in my interviews.

2099
03:16:30,774 --> 03:16:39,457
And when we said 170 journalists are in jail, some of them my friends, and they are also novelists.

2100
03:16:40,137 --> 03:16:43,518
But they are not in jail for writing their novels.

2101
03:16:43,859 --> 03:16:46,820
They're in jail for making political commentary.

2102
03:16:47,260 --> 03:17:00,005
Writing novels, say, in Stalin's time in Russia, we have a lot of repression, a lot of suppression, people self-censor, but people self-censor in interviews, in political comments.

2103
03:17:00,045 --> 03:17:07,768
You'll go fast to jail if you criticize the government too much, if you attack Erdogan too much, you may end up in a jail.

2104
03:17:08,108 --> 03:17:12,311
But I never intend to write a novel attacking a president.

2105
03:17:13,332 --> 03:17:16,094
I never wrote actuality, so to speak.

2106
03:17:16,675 --> 03:17:21,198
So in no sense do you feel creatively paralyzed by the current situation?

2107
03:17:21,298 --> 03:17:23,100
I'm paralyzed, if the word is right.

2108
03:17:23,260 --> 03:17:26,883
I'm repressed, angry, confused.

2109
03:17:26,983 --> 03:17:30,446
Sometimes I feel guilty because I'm out.

2110
03:17:30,526 --> 03:17:31,967
Sometimes I feel angry.

2111
03:17:32,007 --> 03:17:33,188
I have to do more.

2112
03:17:33,568 --> 03:17:35,950
Sometimes... Do you actually literally feel guilty that

2113
03:17:35,990 --> 03:17:39,712
that you are free when some of your writer colleagues are in prison.

2114
03:17:39,852 --> 03:17:46,837
Dostoevsky said that we are responsible for everything, you know, and I think this is the moral writerly thing.

2115
03:17:47,277 --> 03:17:48,057
And then what do you do?

2116
03:17:48,098 --> 03:17:51,059
You look at what the other writers doing in people.

2117
03:17:51,380 --> 03:17:56,523
So there, for example, going to courts, the doors of the courts, or backing, or

2118
03:17:57,143 --> 03:18:01,966
I also did, for example, there is this prominent intellectual, Murat Belget, whom I respect.

2119
03:18:02,226 --> 03:18:03,727
He had a case, so I went there.

2120
03:18:03,747 --> 03:18:06,948
You know, prominent Pamuk is there, so it makes a difference.

2121
03:18:07,229 --> 03:18:09,990
But in the end, this is... Let me tell you this.

2122
03:18:10,250 --> 03:18:18,515
The biggest Turkish newspaper, just before the referendum we had, I think in March or April, asked to do an interview with me.

2123
03:18:18,555 --> 03:18:20,255
Now, I was very happy.

2124
03:18:20,356 --> 03:18:24,478
This is the biggest Turkish newspaper, and they're going to publish my views, and I'm going to say

2125
03:18:25,178 --> 03:18:27,718
no to the referendum, no to Erdogan.

2126
03:18:27,819 --> 03:18:28,259
Very happy.

2127
03:18:28,599 --> 03:18:37,420
We did a nice interview, but then just before the interview, the editor-in-chief, who is a sort of a friend, called me to say, I'm sorry, we can't publish this.

2128
03:18:38,100 --> 03:18:41,081
And really, I cannot accuse the editor too much.

2129
03:18:41,381 --> 03:18:42,581
They're pressured so much.

2130
03:18:42,801 --> 03:18:44,381
And in the end, they're all my friends.

2131
03:18:44,722 --> 03:18:46,422
We are in the same atmosphere.

2132
03:18:46,762 --> 03:18:49,542
And I couldn't address my Turkish readers.

2133
03:18:50,022 --> 03:18:52,363
Therefore, what fascinates me is that you

2134
03:18:53,283 --> 03:19:09,182
This atmosphere you talk about is so constraining when it comes to your public voice as a campaigner as a man who cares about your your national life And yet you're telling me that all of those constraints the anger that you feel the guilt that you feel doesn't affect

2135
03:19:09,582 --> 03:19:23,434
you when you go to your writing room, wherever it is, I know it's in Istanbul, it's in the building that you've occupied for a long time, you go to your writing room and you can shed all of that frustration and that anger and that feeling of constraint and write as free as a bird?

2136
03:19:23,855 --> 03:19:33,083
Not as free as a bird, but let me tell you what the products of this repressive authoritarian air to a writer who is more concerned about the beauty.

2137
03:19:33,843 --> 03:19:39,786
First, you shouldn't read newspapers till 2 o'clock because it spoils your day, you get angry.

2138
03:19:40,606 --> 03:19:46,209
Second, this kind of atmosphere of fear and repression makes me work harder.

2139
03:19:46,949 --> 03:19:55,733
I work harder, just perhaps like in my early years when my family didn't want me a writer and they all accused of me, maybe you're a bohemian, what?

2140
03:19:56,653 --> 03:20:00,955
I worked so hard in these years because I felt guilty about something.

2141
03:20:01,375 --> 03:20:06,181
Again, in the last 15, 16 months, I'm working a lot.

2142
03:20:06,361 --> 03:20:06,681
Why?

2143
03:20:06,862 --> 03:20:08,544
Perhaps to avoid these problems.

2144
03:20:08,804 --> 03:20:17,073
And also, if you write well, even if you're living in a terribly undemocratic, threatening, menacing situation, you feel happy.

2145
03:20:17,454 --> 03:20:21,078
Could you write your books anywhere else but Istanbul?

2146
03:20:21,398 --> 03:20:21,778
I can.

2147
03:20:21,959 --> 03:20:22,499
I did that.

2148
03:20:22,599 --> 03:20:25,462
I'm teaching at Columbia University one semester each year.

2149
03:20:25,662 --> 03:20:33,630
I wrote there and there was a time that I was, remember we also did an interview ten years ago, I was almost a semi-exile.

2150
03:20:33,690 --> 03:20:40,456
You ran into a lot of problems for a while because of things you'd said which were relevant to both the Armenia and Kurdish issues.

2151
03:20:41,617 --> 03:20:44,098
The Turkish government sought to charge you for a while.

2152
03:20:44,158 --> 03:20:45,039
You had to leave the country.

2153
03:20:45,359 --> 03:20:50,501
But it seems to me you always go, in the end, you always go home for creative inspiration.

2154
03:20:50,661 --> 03:20:50,841
Yes.

2155
03:20:51,041 --> 03:20:57,704
Not only that, I also don't want to go to Europe or America and criticize it from distance.

2156
03:20:57,784 --> 03:20:58,544
I don't want that.

2157
03:20:58,844 --> 03:21:00,225
And also there is a reality.

2158
03:21:00,585 --> 03:21:03,346
a reality that feeds my optimism.

2159
03:21:03,386 --> 03:21:05,807
I'll tell you about it perhaps.

2160
03:21:06,107 --> 03:21:11,629
Don't forget that Erdogan's bloc's votes are going down, and the opposition got 49%.

2161
03:21:12,489 --> 03:21:18,711
I am optimistic about the situation, not because there is so much repression, so much repression.

2162
03:21:19,191 --> 03:21:28,214
Also, in the last referendum, I think the referendum was unfair, that is, there was unfair government propaganda.

2163
03:21:28,654 --> 03:21:33,439
In a way, they were taking our tax money and making propaganda for their party.

2164
03:21:33,820 --> 03:21:36,422
But in the end, the results were objective.

2165
03:21:37,103 --> 03:21:40,527
Though it was unfair, the result was objective.

2166
03:21:40,987 --> 03:21:44,571
And if they continue to keep the voting ballot there, I'm there.

2167
03:21:44,691 --> 03:21:45,212
I'm going to come.

2168
03:21:45,432 --> 03:21:46,233
I'll be part of it.

2169
03:21:46,373 --> 03:21:47,494
This is how I think.

2170
03:21:48,497 --> 03:21:58,525
Let me get back to one aspect of this book, The Red-Haired Woman, that again just strikes me as very relevant to your own place in Turkey.

2171
03:21:59,345 --> 03:22:10,334
The key relationship really in the book is between Mahmut the welder, the master welder, and Cem, the assistant who's a student and who comes from a westernized family.

2172
03:22:10,394 --> 03:22:15,538
His father's a leftist and he goes to university and he becomes a property developer.

2173
03:22:15,798 --> 03:22:23,868
So you've got East and you've got tradition juxtaposed with a Western mentality and individualistic liberal sort of background.

2174
03:22:24,669 --> 03:22:34,102
Most people would assume that you yourself, coming from an upper middle class family, as you say, spending time in America, an acclaimed writer, a secularist and a

2175
03:22:34,923 --> 03:22:36,885
you know, a modernist in Turkey.

2176
03:22:37,186 --> 03:22:41,091
Most would assume that you identify completely with the Western tradition in Turkey.

2177
03:22:41,111 --> 03:22:41,472
I do.

2178
03:22:41,792 --> 03:22:42,093
Do you?

2179
03:22:42,213 --> 03:22:47,781
Because the implication of the book is that Turkey draws from all of its history and culture and its different traditions.

2180
03:22:47,801 --> 03:22:49,063
So I wonder what you draw

2181
03:22:49,583 --> 03:22:50,424
from tradition.

2182
03:22:50,764 --> 03:22:54,869
I identify, I believe in Western political values.

2183
03:22:54,909 --> 03:22:55,469
What are they?

2184
03:22:56,150 --> 03:23:02,697
In the end, it's represented by French Revolution slogan, Liberté, Egalité, Fraternité.

2185
03:23:03,978 --> 03:23:05,980
In Turkey, we lack Liberté.

2186
03:23:06,861 --> 03:23:19,030
And some people even claim that in pro-government newspapers they are saying, well, our democracy is not European democracy, we are inventing Turkish democracy, let me add.

2187
03:23:20,231 --> 03:23:24,494
It seems that they're trying to invent a democracy without free speech.

2188
03:23:24,555 --> 03:23:26,716
I don't think it will work, but I'm there.

2189
03:23:26,936 --> 03:23:32,701
I am at least saying this to you, to other journalists in Turkey, outside of Turkey.

2190
03:23:32,961 --> 03:23:35,603
In Turkey they don't print, but they listen somehow.

2191
03:23:35,923 --> 03:23:37,303
Let me talk to you about Istanbul.

2192
03:23:38,023 --> 03:23:45,945
Again, it's almost like it's a character in the book because you describe evocatively how Istanbul changes over 40 years.

2193
03:23:45,965 --> 03:23:50,106
You know, where they dig the well in the first place is a little village outside the city.

2194
03:23:50,146 --> 03:23:51,966
By the end of the book, it's just another suburb.

2195
03:23:51,986 --> 03:23:52,867
Swallowed by the city.

2196
03:23:52,947 --> 03:23:58,608
Sucked up by the city with its industrial zones and its high-rises and its condos and everything else.

2197
03:24:00,030 --> 03:24:06,093
Has the change in Istanbul changed the people and the character of the city?

2198
03:24:06,113 --> 03:24:06,673
Good question.

2199
03:24:06,734 --> 03:24:17,659
OK, first, the change, and this is Erdogan's success, the change in last 15 years is bigger than the change in my first 50 years of my life.

2200
03:24:18,179 --> 03:24:28,325
That is, I also want to argue, especially to my Western journalist friend, key to his success, as much as religion is his success,

2201
03:24:29,185 --> 03:24:33,526
But on the other hand, this party is saying they're conservative, and they're not.

2202
03:24:33,746 --> 03:24:38,127
And besides, the religious buildings and mosques, they're not conserving anything, they're destroying everything.

2203
03:24:38,567 --> 03:24:50,430
The city had turned out to be a sea of baton, and I'd love to ask them, well, you were conservatives, and it's not only religious buildings that should be preserved.

2204
03:24:50,630 --> 03:24:53,651
Where is the old Istanbul you were so lovingly talking about?

2205
03:24:54,112 --> 03:25:07,808
There is also, this book is going into that, money and politics combined in construction businesses, and of course leading party, ruling party, people who are close around this benefit from these.

2206
03:25:09,390 --> 03:25:11,211
Do you feel it's still your city?

2207
03:25:11,231 --> 03:25:12,491
It is.

2208
03:25:12,711 --> 03:25:13,551
It's geographically.

2209
03:25:13,571 --> 03:25:14,612
It's my city.

2210
03:25:15,012 --> 03:25:16,632
I am looking at its entrance.

2211
03:25:16,752 --> 03:25:17,693
I have a great view.

2212
03:25:18,293 --> 03:25:19,393
It's changing, yes.

2213
03:25:20,273 --> 03:25:22,634
The hills overlooking Bosphorus, I see that now.

2214
03:25:22,754 --> 03:25:27,016
Behind them, they are preserving at least the hills overlooking Bosphorus, the gardens.

2215
03:25:27,256 --> 03:25:31,377
But behind them, all the high-rises are grazing there, and it's changing.

2216
03:25:31,697 --> 03:25:33,480
But I cannot say that it's not my city.

2217
03:25:33,840 --> 03:25:42,232
Yes, also it's a self-imposed ethical mission that I don't want to be a nostalgic middle-class Turkish westernized secular.

2218
03:25:43,053 --> 03:25:45,697
They only look at the newcomers, immigrants.

2219
03:25:46,858 --> 03:25:47,639
you're destroying.

2220
03:25:48,379 --> 03:25:49,740
I don't want to even see you.

2221
03:25:50,141 --> 03:25:50,461
Why?

2222
03:25:50,761 --> 03:25:55,645
Just like in Germany, they need labour and also they look down upon them.

2223
03:25:56,086 --> 03:26:00,789
From the beginning, I didn't want to belong to my class.

2224
03:26:01,150 --> 03:26:07,174
I betrayed my class because I want to see the totality of the nation in an ethical way.

2225
03:26:07,234 --> 03:26:09,896
But only somebody of your class could say that sort of thing.

2226
03:26:09,917 --> 03:26:10,237
I mean,

2227
03:26:10,677 --> 03:26:18,263
That is the irony of being so full of self-awareness and education that you can talk about not wanting to be of your class.

2228
03:26:18,303 --> 03:26:19,964
You are quintessentially of your class.

2229
03:26:20,224 --> 03:26:28,630
And that's the problem, perhaps, for some people in Turkey, that however hard you try, you cannot help but be what you are, which is a member of the elite.

2230
03:26:29,531 --> 03:26:38,318
It started with Snow that, in that book, 65% of Turkey's population has not political, some kind of headgear, headscarf.

2231
03:26:39,138 --> 03:26:44,679
And even in early 2000s, they did not allow these people to universities.

2232
03:26:45,139 --> 03:26:49,260
And then they thought the secular parties, they would get votes from the people.

2233
03:26:49,681 --> 03:26:57,762
They paid way for the success of Erdogan's party, for their cruel, authoritarian attitudes.

2234
03:26:57,842 --> 03:27:01,743
Now, Erdogan is even more, getting even more authoritarian now.

2235
03:27:02,183 --> 03:27:08,445
But whenever, I sometimes argue, whenever these two sides clash, I can find a space in between

2236
