2316
03:35:13,385 --> 03:35:28,188
the beginning of a ceremony called the Parati where the crew is going to bring in their boat from the ice symbolizing that they're done whaling for the season and they're gonna hand out fermented whale, some soup.

2317
03:35:37,045 --> 03:35:39,527
I just said, welcome, everybody.

2318
03:35:39,547 --> 03:35:42,189
I am Naomi Asok, and I'm from Barrow.

2319
03:35:42,829 --> 03:35:43,469
Naomi is 23.

2320
03:35:44,530 --> 03:35:49,533
She hunts walrus, seal, caribou, and whale with her father, Herman.

2321
03:35:49,974 --> 03:35:53,116
When you harvest a whale, you can't sell the meat or muktak.

2322
03:35:53,816 --> 03:35:56,398
It's given away to everybody, everybody.

2323
03:35:56,939 --> 03:35:58,640
Even if you don't belong to a whaling crew,

2324
03:35:59,360 --> 03:36:01,482
and you go up and butcher the whale, you get a share.

2325
03:36:02,283 --> 03:36:09,850
You can't sell it because it's the International Whaling Commission law, because we use it as subsistence.

2326
03:36:10,607 --> 03:36:20,433
The success and safety of a hunting season here depends on the local knowledge of the ice, as it forms, solidifies and breaks up over the course of a winter.

2327
03:36:21,033 --> 03:36:28,438
Ice is siku in Inupiaq, and there's also the tuak, which is the ice that's connected to the shore.

2328
03:36:28,998 --> 03:36:32,080
And then the salvi is the main pack that travels with the current.

2329
03:36:41,749 --> 03:36:43,511
These names are important.

2330
03:36:43,931 --> 03:36:55,802
They allow the hunters to communicate, to tell each other where they can walk, where they can drive their trucks and where they can gut their prey in a landscape that merges for most of the year with the Arctic Ocean.

2331
03:36:56,543 --> 03:37:04,569
There was a lot of different changes within just my 23 years of existing at home.

2332
03:37:05,389 --> 03:37:07,111
The ice is changing.

2333
03:37:07,391 --> 03:37:09,432
It's changing so fast.

2334
03:37:10,473 --> 03:37:13,935
The coastline has eroded so fast.

2335
03:37:15,196 --> 03:37:24,658
And it's a little bit more challenging trying to go caribou hunting with the four-wheelers along the coast because of the erosion.

2336
03:37:24,678 --> 03:37:35,201
And we're trying to have to work around the thawing and around the breaking of ice.

2337
03:37:35,281 --> 03:37:37,901
And we have to be very careful.

2338
03:37:39,142 --> 03:37:40,122
We have a hammer up there?

2339
03:37:43,355 --> 03:37:48,697
The whales that are caught in the short hunting season feed the community here right through the year.

2340
03:37:49,458 --> 03:38:01,583
In a town where an omelette in a cafe costs 20 US dollars, the whale meat, traditionally kept frozen at the bottom of a four meter shaft drilled through the ice, is a vital food source.

2341
03:38:01,603 --> 03:38:02,323
Let's have a look.

2342
03:38:03,093 --> 03:38:06,454
This is our traditional ice cellar.

2343
03:38:07,154 --> 03:38:10,894
This is where we store our muktuk and our meat from the bowhead whale.

2344
03:38:11,555 --> 03:38:15,235
It's 20 feet down, and it's a natural freezer.

2345
03:38:15,815 --> 03:38:23,177
Whenever a crew is successful catching a whale, they'll put the excess meat and muktuk in here, the blubber.

2346
03:38:23,737 --> 03:38:25,117
And there's a difference, you can tell.

2347
03:38:25,137 --> 03:38:30,818
Like, if you put the meat in a traditional freezer, like in your home, you'll actually

2348
03:38:31,878 --> 03:38:35,620
You can taste where it's been sitting, but it tastes really good.

2349
03:38:35,660 --> 03:38:36,720
It's like the earth.

2350
03:38:37,480 --> 03:38:40,361
But the permafrost here is no longer reliable.

2351
03:38:41,062 --> 03:38:44,783
There's water instead of ice at the bottom of Naomi's cellar.

2352
03:38:45,603 --> 03:38:51,666
There's some that are not working anymore because of the changing weather.

2353
03:38:59,267 --> 03:39:13,692
Travel across the Arctic Ocean, over the North Pole, and you reach Svalbard, a group of islands administered by Norway, but home to research stations belonging to France, Germany, Russia, the UK, and even China.

2354
03:39:14,792 --> 03:39:21,655
With so many scientists here, the melting of the ice and the thawing of the permafrost are monitored very carefully.

2355
03:39:22,195 --> 03:39:34,700
So it was relatively cold here in Svalbard in the 60s and in the 80s and then after that for the last 35 years we have seen a more or less persistent temperature increase up here.

2356
03:39:35,020 --> 03:39:39,704
Ole Humlen is a geographer at UNIS, the university centre in Svalbard.

2357
03:39:40,424 --> 03:39:45,168
This was what we had in the beginning at UNIS, the only room where we could work on frozen samples.

2358
03:39:45,388 --> 03:39:48,430
Ole is married to geology professor Hannah Christensen.

2359
03:39:48,690 --> 03:39:51,172
It's minus 17 in the freezer today.

2360
03:39:51,332 --> 03:39:56,156
She keeps her core samples from the Svalbard permafrost in a walk-in freezer at UNIS.

2361
03:39:56,416 --> 03:40:08,540
Not only do we measure the temperature of the permafrost in Svalbard, but we're also monitoring and measuring the thickness of the thawed layer, the active layer on top of the permafrost that develops every summer when energy is provided to the ground.

2362
03:40:09,160 --> 03:40:10,941
And then we can monitor that.

2363
03:40:11,041 --> 03:40:12,561
And we've been doing that for 15, 16 years now.

2364
03:40:14,422 --> 03:40:25,806
So we know that on average over that period of time where temperatures have gone up, we see an increase in the thickness of the active layer of around half a centimeter to a centimeter, of course varies between years.

2365
03:40:26,566 --> 03:40:31,768
So that means that we're losing that amount of permafrost from this area that we are monitoring like that.

2366
03:40:32,208 --> 03:40:38,892
Thawing permafrost can release the climate-warming gas methane, which is even more damaging than carbon dioxide.

2367
03:40:39,713 --> 03:40:41,474
It also causes local problems.

2368
03:40:41,994 --> 03:40:50,239
