2427
03:47:13,894 --> 03:47:16,235
It's all been quenched by the seawater.

2428
03:47:16,395 --> 03:47:19,917
Amazing, thick soup of plankton.

2429
03:47:20,397 --> 03:47:21,638
And it's mainly animal plankton.

2430
03:47:21,938 --> 03:47:22,918
And they're tiny.

2431
03:47:23,018 --> 03:47:25,660
It's hard for me to make out what we're seeing here.

2432
03:47:25,680 --> 03:47:28,241
That's a larval fish that's just gone by the sphere there.

2433
03:47:29,101 --> 03:47:30,162
Tiny little crustaceans.

2434
03:47:30,182 --> 03:47:31,762
They're kind of like the insects of the ocean.

2435
03:47:31,883 --> 03:47:33,463
Control, control, rover.

2436
03:47:33,543 --> 03:47:34,904
Both subs off bottom.

2437
03:47:34,984 --> 03:47:36,205
Depth 4-0-0 meters, over.

2438
03:47:39,190 --> 03:47:42,792
Where we are right now, mid-water, this is a very strange place.

2439
03:47:43,052 --> 03:47:49,055
It's a world without war, so there are animals that live their whole lives here, never touching a solid, hard surface.

2440
03:47:49,256 --> 03:47:53,338
And that means they've got bodies that are like blown glass, that are sort of ethereal.

2441
03:47:53,358 --> 03:47:56,840
A lot of them are bodies very delicate, made of jelly.

2442
03:47:57,480 --> 03:47:59,721
And the only way to understand the life here is to come and see it.

2443
03:48:00,081 --> 03:48:04,604
Because if you try and fish these up with a net, all you get is a lot of snot in the bottom of the net.

2444
03:48:05,284 --> 03:48:06,545
Oh, look at that ice fish there.

2445
03:48:06,725 --> 03:48:07,705
Crocodile ice fish.

2446
03:48:07,765 --> 03:48:09,806
That's a beauty.

2447
03:48:10,507 --> 03:48:13,748
And it has a... Its snout is really like crocodile-like.

2448
03:48:14,869 --> 03:48:20,071
Just everywhere we go, there is something amazing and something different.

2449
03:48:24,648 --> 03:48:26,989
Oh, the krill are really starting to swarm around us now.

2450
03:48:27,009 --> 03:48:29,490
I mean, they're almost see-through.

2451
03:48:29,510 --> 03:48:44,055
You sometimes catch a flash of what's in their gut, a little line down the body, and they've actually got little organs like headlights dotted along their bodies as well, which when we switch out the lights later, hopefully we'll be able to see some of their firework displays.

2452
03:48:44,615 --> 03:48:48,557
Control, Rover, that's both subs finished, standing by to leave bottom hour.

2453
03:48:52,543 --> 03:48:56,066
Those krill are the foundation of life in the Antarctic.

2454
03:48:56,467 --> 03:49:01,971
Food for the seals, the whales and the penguins that live on the West Antarctic Peninsula.

2455
03:49:02,932 --> 03:49:06,095
This is one of the fastest warming areas on Earth.

2456
03:49:06,836 --> 03:49:09,378
Warming temperatures means less sea ice.

2457
03:49:09,898 --> 03:49:14,002
Less sea ice means less habitat for the algae that the krill eat.

2458
03:49:14,722 --> 03:49:19,767
And that could be catastrophic for the mammals and birds in this part of the Southern Ocean.

2459
03:49:21,080 --> 03:49:23,081
You know, really, it's amazing.

2460
03:49:23,361 --> 03:49:27,522
There are so many wandering albatrosses behind this boat now, I can't describe.

2461
03:49:28,282 --> 03:49:31,183
They're the world's largest bird in terms of wingspan.

2462
03:49:31,203 --> 03:49:33,144
They're three, three and a half meters.

2463
03:49:33,744 --> 03:49:35,505
And they come just alongside the boat.

2464
03:49:35,805 --> 03:49:39,926
And they sort of, they just float, just almost within fingertip reach of them.

2465
03:49:40,406 --> 03:49:44,828
They just look at you as they sort of glide gently up to see what you're all about.

2466
03:49:45,948 --> 03:49:51,874
and then fire off across the surface of the ocean, almost skimming the surface of the sea with their wingtips.

2467
03:49:51,914 --> 03:49:55,938
They're just extraordinarily capable birds in the air.

2468
03:49:56,119 --> 03:50:00,203
They look like they're applying no effort to the mechanism of flight whatsoever.

2469
03:50:01,232 --> 03:50:03,594
Gerard Baker is a chef and a writer.

2470
03:50:03,995 --> 03:50:12,322
He's been working in the Southern Ocean for 23 years on cruise ships, fishing boats, and in the British Antarctic Survey's research stations.

2471
03:50:13,163 --> 03:50:17,287
In a region with no permanent residents, Gerard qualifies as a local.

2472
03:50:17,728 --> 03:50:22,152
And like most of us, he cares about the future of life on his own doorstep.

2473
03:50:24,233 --> 03:50:32,797
We've been stalked by a foot and a half long, fluffy, slightly damp-looking fur seal pup with teeth about a millimetre long.

2474
03:50:32,817 --> 03:50:39,620
So although it makes a growly, aggressive kind of noise, it might nibble the end of your boot, but not much more than that.

2475
03:50:41,800 --> 03:50:44,162
This is one of the more unusual treasure hunts I've ever been on.

2476
03:50:44,202 --> 03:50:50,269
We're hunting for fur seal scats, or faeces, here on the snow at King Edward Point.

2477
03:50:50,289 --> 03:50:56,815
And I'm with the zoologist here, Kieran, who is going to show me what he does with this.

2478
03:50:56,835 --> 03:51:00,920
He's got a plastic bag on one hand and there's a dirty brown lump on the snow.

2479
03:51:00,940 --> 03:51:01,580
Kieran, you go ahead.

2480
03:51:01,600 --> 03:51:04,924
Tell me, what's the point of collecting the fur seal scats?

2481
03:51:05,584 --> 03:51:21,747
So the whole point to this is to analyse their diet, to understand exactly what they're eating, and this can indicate then how much krill and fish and potentially squid is in the waters here in South Georgia.

2482
03:51:22,407 --> 03:51:23,587
OK, well, you go ahead and pick up.

2483
03:51:24,367 --> 03:51:31,428
So there's absolutely no skill towards this, same as what you would do with your own dog.

2484
03:51:32,909 --> 03:51:34,449
And this one is basically...

2485
03:51:37,255 --> 03:51:39,596
It's nicely frozen onto the snow there.

2486
03:51:41,797 --> 03:51:43,918
Dog owners will be sympathetic to you at this point.

2487
03:51:45,399 --> 03:51:57,704
The reason Kieran, who works for the South Georgia government, is so interested in krill numbers, is that krill fishing is on the increase, as the world's human population craves new sources of omega-3 oils.

2488
03:51:58,564 --> 03:52:04,027
The warming climate means that fishing boats can work further south, deeper into the Antarctic winter.

2489
03:52:05,182 --> 03:52:11,585
Crucially, the Norwegians have developed a cunning way of catching the krill and freezing them whilst they're still completely fresh.

2490
03:52:12,385 --> 03:52:19,808
That makes them fit for human consumption, so you'll now see krill oil high in omega-3 in a lot of health food shops around the world.

2491
03:52:20,648 --> 03:52:25,450
The Chinese and South Koreans are now following the Norwegians into the southern waters.

2492
03:52:27,556 --> 03:52:35,125
Well, I've come to Nikko Harbour on the western coast of the Antarctic Peninsula, and here it's a large Gentoo penguin colony.

2493
03:52:35,285 --> 03:52:41,632
There are adults wandering around, chicks, large chicks now, it's mid-season, and they're beginning to fledge.

2494
03:52:43,014 --> 03:52:48,100
And all around is evidence of krill and iguana on the ground in between the rocks here.

2495
03:52:49,748 --> 03:52:53,890
Oh, there's a glacier carving in the background, a little bit of wave happening.

2496
03:52:55,611 --> 03:53:04,355
It's hard not to connect the success, the breeding success of the penguins here on shore with what's happening out there on the water.

2497
03:53:06,236 --> 03:53:13,560
Here at Neco Harbour last year, along with other nearby islands like Cooverville, almost all of the Gentoo chicks died from starvation.

2498
03:53:17,411 --> 03:53:23,535
This is one of the cameras, and as you can see, there's a bunch of nests in view.

2499
03:53:25,175 --> 03:53:26,096
And this is the cool one.

2500
03:53:26,196 --> 03:53:34,701
It takes a photo every hour all year, which shows when they arrive, when they depart, and the reproductive success, so which chicks survive and which don't.

2501
03:53:35,922 --> 03:53:45,787
Using a network of cameras, Tom Hart from Oxford University monitors the three species of brushtail penguin on the Antarctic Peninsula, the chinstrap, a dayleaf, and gen2.

2502
03:53:47,208 --> 03:53:49,549
Every summer, he visits the cameras to change the batteries.

2503
03:53:50,490 --> 03:53:57,493
In the spring of 2016, he noticed a sharp decline in the number of chicks successfully fledged on Cooverville Island.

2504
03:53:59,374 --> 03:54:02,695
Cooverville Island has about 2,000 gentoo penguins on it.

2505
03:54:03,295 --> 03:54:06,557
And there was a big die-off there right at the end of the season.

2506
03:54:07,497 --> 03:54:09,498
So I'd come back, I didn't see it.

2507
03:54:10,619 --> 03:54:13,320
But we started getting all these reports of a die-off.

2508
03:54:14,492 --> 03:54:16,373
So what caused the southern penguin die-off?

2509
03:54:17,133 --> 03:54:23,395
The evidence, according to scientists at the nearby Palmer Research Station, suggests it wasn't disease, but starvation.

2510
03:54:24,475 --> 03:54:26,056
That points to a problem with the krill.

2511
03:54:27,116 --> 03:54:31,918
They could have suffered their own bad breeding year, or returning whales could have taken a larger share.

2512
03:54:33,233 --> 03:54:35,394
Climate change is another of the key suspects.

2513
03:54:36,314 --> 03:54:38,535
Mark Belsher from the British Antarctic Survey.

2514
03:54:39,155 --> 03:54:48,358
Climate change is likely to have a very large impact on all aspects of the Southern Ocean ecosystem, not least in Antarctic krill.

2515
03:54:49,399 --> 03:54:55,121
They are very much dependent for their early life history stages on the northerly extent of sea ice.

2516
03:54:55,918 --> 03:54:59,540
where their spawning and egg duration phase takes place.

2517
03:55:00,060 --> 03:55:14,807
So clearly the location of the ice edge and the timing of the extent of the ice edge will have a major impact as to where krill ultimately will end up in the Southern Ocean, which currents they get entrained in, and indeed their overall success.

2518
03:55:15,407 --> 03:55:19,709
Brent Stewart from the Hubb Seaworld Research Institute also expects an impact.

2519
03:55:20,289 --> 03:55:37,425
Well, I think the key here with all the discussion about changes in climate, which is clearly happening, local changes in climate, regional changes in climate, oceanographic climate or atmospheric climate, is the question is how quickly does it happen and do animals have the, can they respond to it?

2520
03:55:37,786 --> 03:55:41,149
Some will respond to it well and some won't if it happens very quickly.

2521
03:55:41,209 --> 03:55:45,233
So if the climate changes quickly enough that it

2522
03:55:45,953 --> 03:55:57,180
degrades the habitat for krill, which are the primary food source for a lot of things, and that just vanishes, then that's going to be a very, very sudden change for the predators.

2523
03:55:57,500 --> 03:55:59,701
They'll either move elsewhere or they won't do so well.

2524
03:56:00,402 --> 03:56:06,425
So climate change is likely to affect the krill, but it may be premature to blame it for a single bad year.

2525
03:56:07,286 --> 03:56:09,087
Another suspect is the fishing industry.

2526
03:56:09,787 --> 03:56:14,670
Large krill fishing boats were seen working close to the penguin colonies at the time of the die-off.

2527
03:56:15,150 --> 03:56:18,431
Trying to pin the blame on any one event is really hard.

2528
03:56:19,252 --> 03:56:33,418
It was possibly a bad krill year but there was also a lot of fishing going on nearby and yeah that to me absolutely highlights the problem that you can have associations and that's not evidence either way.

2529
03:56:34,685 --> 03:56:38,488
So far, there's no firm evidence that krill numbers have declined in the Southern Ocean.

2530
03:56:39,089 --> 03:56:42,872
It's very difficult to gather accurate data over such a huge area.

2531
03:56:44,033 --> 03:56:48,956
What worries Tom is that the birds and mammals are concentrated in particular parts of the ocean.

2532
03:56:49,877 --> 03:56:54,101
If fishing boats target exactly the same area, then food could run short.

2533
03:56:57,467 --> 03:57:06,715
Yeah, so all of these predators, they're land-based, raising their young on land, so they're tied to the land like an aircraft carrier.

2534
03:57:07,035 --> 03:57:13,640
They can go out and they can fish, they can go foraging, but they need to come back to land where they're young are to raise their young.

2535
03:57:14,481 --> 03:57:24,870
All different species, so this could be Adelie penguins, Chinstrap penguins and Gentoo penguins, but also Crabbeater seals, anything apart from whales, they're land-based when they're breeding.

2536
03:57:26,332 --> 03:57:29,175
and doing these little forays out to get food.

2537
03:57:29,195 --> 03:57:36,301
The penguins all around me are witnesses to what's happening in the Southern Ocean.

2538
03:57:37,202 --> 03:57:44,408
The future health of this colony and others like it is very dependent on climate change and ultimately what we as humans do.

2539
03:57:47,703 --> 03:57:53,625
I'm Liz Bonnen and you've been listening to Ocean Stories for the Compass from the BBC World Service.

2540
03:57:54,605 --> 03:57:56,646
The producer was Alistair Cross.

